Challenges of a Bike Sharing Business Model¶

by Caspar Heidbrink¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This is my project "Communicate Data Findings" in course of taking Udacity's Data Analyst Nanodegree.

A underlying data for this project, I chosed the data from Ford GoBike System which now is being operated by Lyft and just recently under the name baywheels.

What Is Baywheels All About?¶

Since August 2013, baywheels and its predecessors (Motivate which cooperated with General Motors/Ford and which was then acquired by Lyft) offer bike sharing services in the Californian Bay Area in the USA, namely in

  • San Francisco
  • Easy Bay and
  • San Jose

The offering of baywheels include short term rental services for bikes also known as bike sharing. The fleet currently consists of three types of bikes, docked standard bikes, docked electric-assistet bikes and dockless standard bikes with a rear-wheel lock (which are reported to be offered solely in San Jose).

The services are being offered to individual and corporate subscribers as well as for casual customers.

bayweels has a contract with the Bay's Metropolitan Transportation Commission which grants exclusive rights for bike sharing - however, just recently there started a dispute weather this is limited to docked bikes or not. This dispute is reported to affect operations. Until today there's only competition by JUMP from Uber, which offers dockless bikes and e-bikes in a smaller pilot programm, but the City of San Francisco wants to significantly extend bike sharing (including dockless) and is aiming to more involve competitors. Also the deployment of brand-new ebikes had severe problems.

A brief description of the activities including a history of partners involved can also be found on wikipedia.

Motivation¶

As I know from my hometown, Berlin/Germany, bike sharing is indeed a growing business. Bike sharing has a notion of being an environmentally friendly, healthy and fun alternative to other modes of transport.

However, I assume that bike sharing is also a challenging business model.

  • Of course, it would be interesting if the data would show proof of the reported operational issues in connection with the legal dispute between baywheels and the City of San Francisco.
  • Amongst others, a challenging aspect may be the operation of a decentralized system (even if it's at least partly bound to docks), where the bikes come in and go out kind of randomly and often must be reallocated.

The Data¶

As I want to investigate on the challenges of a bike sharing business model, it is great that baywheels offers system data here.

Data with many broadly described specifications regarding trips from 2017 up to (as of today) June 2019 can be found there. The data is spread in 18 csv files, most of them zipped, but one unzipped having a size of 118 MB. I downloaded the files and saved them in the folder 'data' (and zipped the unzipped file then sizing 18MB in order to comply with GitHubs file size limits).

Now, let's see if the data is helpful for my investigation, but first we'll need import some useful libraries for our quest:

# Function to load all csvs from a folder into one dataframe
def concat_df_from_csvfolder(folder: str, **kwargs)-> pd.DataFrame:

    # Also working for compressed files
    if 'compression' in kwargs:
        extension = kwargs['compression']
    else:
        extension = 'csv'
    
    # Get list of csv paths in folder
    csvs = glob.glob(folder + '/*.' + extension)
    
    # Initialize list for dfs from csvs
    dfs = []
    
    # Iterate over list of csv paths
    for csv in csvs:
        
        # Get df from csv using kwargs
        df = pd.read_csv(csv, **kwargs)
        
        # Append df to dfs
        dfs.append(df)
        
    # Concatenate all dfs
    df = pd.concat(dfs, 
                   axis=0, 
                   ignore_index=True, 
                   sort=False)
    
    return df

Structure of the dataset¶

The dataset retrieved from 19 csvs/zips from baywheels contains information for 3.628.260 trips/rows with the following 17 attributes/columns:

Attribute Description Strategy
'duration_sec' Duration of the ride in seconds Keep
'start_time' Start time of the ride Keep, convert to Timedelta
'end_time' Id of the station where the ride started Eliminate (possible redundancy to 'start_time' and 'duration'
'start_station_id' Name of the station where the ride started Eliminate, rely on 'start_latitude' and 'start_longitude'
'start_station_name' Name of the station where the ride started Eliminate, rely on 'start_latitude' and 'start_longitude'
'start_station_latitude' Geografical latitude of the station where the ride started Keep
'start_station_longitude' Geografical longitude of the station where the ride started Keep
'end_station_id' Id of the station where the ride started Eliminate, rely on 'end_latitude' and 'end_longitude'
'end_station_name' Name of the station where the ride started Eliminate, rely on 'end_latitude' and 'end_longitude'
'end_station_latitude' Geografical latitude of the station where the ride started Keep
'end_station_longitude' Geografical longitude of the station where the ride started Keep
'bike_id' Id of the bike Keep
'user_type' Type of the user (being 'Subscriber' or 'Customer'/casual rider Keep, convert to category
'member_birth_year' Year of birth of the user Keep
'member_gender' Gender of the user Keep; convert to category
'bike_share_for_all_trip' User being a member of the 'Bike Share for All' program (special subscription program) Keep; convert to category; inner structure with 'user_type'
'rental_access_method' Interface the rental contract is being generated with Eliminate as it was introduced in 06/2019

In order to simplify the further analysis, I first create a new dataframe 'trip_data' with columns according to the defined strategy:

# Map user values

trip_data.gender.replace({np.NaN: 'Unknown'}, inplace=True)
trip_data.gender.replace({'M': 'Male', 'F': 'Female', 'O': 'Other', '?': 'Unknown'}, inplace=True)
In [16]:
# Downsize int for bike to necessary size
trip_data.bike = trip_data.bike.astype('int32')

# Set gender as category
trip_data.gender = trip_data.gender.astype('category')

# Reducing precision of time data to minutes
trip_data.start_time = trip_data.start_time.astype('datetime64[m]')
trip_data.duration = pd.to_timedelta((trip_data.duration/60).apply(np.floor)*60, unit='s')

# Reduce precision of lat/long to around 0.0002 (which only is approx. 60 feet)
trip_data[['start_lat', 'start_long', 'end_lat', 'end_long']] = (trip_data[['start_lat', 'start_long', 'end_lat', 'end_long']] / 2).round(4) * 2

Feature(s) of interest¶

As my pursuit is rather broad and it's less about finding the drivers of one single feature, all features (user related ones, time related ones and location related ones) will play a role.

Now, let's start the investigation:

Time Related Features:¶

Interim Conclusion(s):

  • The business grew strongly, almost quadrupling the number of trips per month!
  • However, second (full year) was weaker and after a severe drop in number of trips in May, the last two months were comparably week - this may relate to the reported issues (bike shortage, bad press in San Francisco due to law suit).

data = trip_data[(trip_data.start_time >= '2017-07-01') & 
                 (trip_data.start_time < '2019-07-01')]
data = data[['start_time', 'duration']]

data['year'] = 0
data.loc[(trip_data.start_time >= '2018-07-01') & 
         (trip_data.start_time < '2019-07-01'), 'year'] = 1

# Duration in minutes rather than seconds
data.duration = data.duration.dt.total_seconds() / 60

# Bins for every doubling of 1 minute
bin_edges = 2 ** np.arange(0, np.log2(2048), 1)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, figsize=(10,10))

for i in range(2):
    ax[i].hist(data[data.year == i]['duration'], bins=bin_edges)
    ax[i].set_xscale('log', basex=2)
    xtick_locs = [1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256, 512, 1024, 2048]
    ax[i].set_xticks(xtick_locs)
    ax[i].set_xticklabels(xtick_locs)
    ax[i].set_title('year: ' + str(i))

Interim Conclusion(s):
When comparing the first (full) year, with the second (with more users), we don't see a drastic change in duration of the trips.

Interim Conclusion(s):
Trips in San Francisco are a bit longer than in East Bay and San Jose. However, there they also tend to be below 16 minutes (15 minutes being a threshold for further charges).

Interim Summary:¶

  • Non-subscribers show a more homogenous pattern of usage during the day and tend to use the bikes longer.
  • Whilst usage of both, subscribers and non-subscribers, dropped in May 2019, only non-subscribers bounced back in June.
  • There are three operating areas, San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose, with San Francisco being the most significant one.
  • The drop in trips in San Francisco and East Bay in May 2019 also stays on in June 2019, whilst (more growing, but overall least significant) San Jose could recover.

def scatter_sfeb_data(condition=None, cbar_min_max=None, circle_scale_factor=None):
    
    if condition is not None:
        data = sfeb_data[condition].copy()
    else:
        data = sfeb_data.copy()
    
    start_loc_freq = (data.
                      groupby(['start_lat', 'start_long']).count()['counts'])
    end_loc_freq = (data.
                    groupby(['end_lat', 'end_long']).
                    count()['counts'])
    
    loc_freq = pd.DataFrame(pd.concat([start_loc_freq, end_loc_freq], 
                                      axis=1, sort=True).
                            sum(axis=1))
    loc_freq.columns = ['freq']
    
    loc_delta = pd.DataFrame(pd.concat([-start_loc_freq, end_loc_freq], 
                                       axis=1, sort=True).
                             sum(axis=1))
    loc_delta.columns = ['delta']

    loc_data = (pd.concat([loc_freq, loc_delta], 
                          axis=1).
                fillna(0).
                reset_index())
    loc_data.columns = ['lat', 'long', 'freq', 'delta']
    loc_data['source'] = loc_data.delta / loc_data.freq
    
    if cbar_min_max is None:
        cbar_min_max = max(-loc_data.source.min(), loc_data.source.max())
        
    if circle_scale_factor is None:
        circle_scale_factor = loc_data.freq.max() / 250
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax.set_facecolor('dimgrey')
    plt.scatter(x=loc_data.long, y=loc_data.lat, 
                s=loc_data.freq / circle_scale_factor, 
                c=loc_data.source, cmap='RdBu', vmin=-cbar_min_max, vmax=cbar_min_max, 
                alpha=0.8)
    
    plt.colorbar();

  • There's a need for actively relocating the bikes from one station to another.
